<HEADLINE>
GOV'T TO ELIMINATE HIGH ENERGY CONSUMING LIGHT BULBS BY 2010
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Feb.  13 (CNA) 02/13/07  20:59:47 (By T.C. Jiang)
</P>
<P>
The government will adopt a stricter standard for electricity-
conserving light bulbs starting by 2010, with the aim of using
the more energy-efficient light bulbs, officials from the Bureau
of Energy under the Ministry of Economic Affairs (MOEA) said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new plan is part of the government's efforts to deal with
global warming and to conserve energy, according to the
officials.
</P>
<P>
The new standard is higher than those set in the United States,
South Korea and China, the officials noted, adding that a total
of 43 million kWh of electricity could be saved each year, which
amounts to a reduction of 29,900 metric tons of carbon dioxide
emissions.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's electricity consumption for lighting is rising, and
already accounts for more than 10 percent of total electricity
consumption, bureau officials pointed out.
</P>
<P>
As a result, it is important that the government to follow other
countries' footsteps in regulating the energy efficiency of
lighting products, the officials stressed.
</P>
